de.ovgu.featureide.fm.core.base

Interface IFeature

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IEventManager, IFeatureModelElement
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AFeature, ExtendedFeature, Feature, Feature

    public interface IFeature
extends IFeatureModelElement
    The feature interface represents any class that acts in the sense of a feature in FeatureIDE. A feature contains both
    • certain fixed properties (e.g., its name) which are available by the features implementation of IFeatureProperty, and
    • custom properties which can be stored and received in a key-value store like fashion without the need of modifying existing code
    Each feature belongs to other features where statements between features form a feature model. Hence, a feature is related to a structure which connects the feature to, e.g., it's children, or it's parent feature in terms of these statements. Any feature is highly related to it's name and identified by it's internal identifier. The last both properties are mixed-in with the IFeatureModelElement interface. An instance of IFeature intended to be instantiated by a IFeatureModelFactory.

    FeatureIDE provides an adapter implementation AFeature which is a abstract base class and which should be prefered as starting point for custom implementations. This base class contains ready-to-use implementations for both IFeature and IFeatureModelElement.

    Example
    The following example demonstrate the creation of a new feature called FeatureA using FeatureIDE's default IFeature implementation Feature, and the corresponding default factory DefaultFeatureModelFactory over the conviennent factory class FMFactoryManager: IFeatureModel model = FMFactoryManager.getFactory().createFeatureModel(); IFeature feature = FMFactoryManager.getFactory().createFeature(model, "FeatureA"); A unified handling of certain IFeature implementations (in terms of conviennent methods) can be achieved with the use of FeatureUtils helper class.

    API notes: The classes internal structure has heavily changed compared to older FeatureIDE version. A bridge to the old-fashioned handling is available in FeatureUtils as static methods.

    Notes on equals method: Any implementation have to provide a Object.equals(Object) implementation when the feature implementation should be fully useable in the FeatureIDE system (and therefore, have to be an instance of IFeatureModelElement), which at least returns true when the internal identifier of two features are the same, and otherwise false.

    Compatibility Notes: To provide compatibility to earlier versions of FeatureIDE, the out-dated class Feature also implements the IFeature interface. Developers should neither use nor extend this obsolete class since it is deprecated and will be removed in one of the next versions.
    Since:
    3.0
    Author:
    Sebastian Krieter, Marcus Pinnecke
    See Also:
    Default implementation of IFeature (as starting point for custom implementations), Interface for feature constraints (IConstraint), Interface for feature models (IFeatureModel), Interface for feature properties (IFeatureProperty), Interface for a feature's structure (IFeatureStructure), Default implementation for feature constraints (AConstraint), Default implementation for feature models (FeatureModel), Default implementation for feature properties (FeatureProperty), Default implementation for a feature's structure (FeatureStructure)

    • Method Detail

      • clone

        IFeature clone(IFeatureModel newFeatureModel,
               IFeatureStructure newStructure)
        Creates a new instance (new reference) of this feature with the same feature name and internal id, optionally change the features feature model and/or structure.
        Parameters:
        newFeatureModel - A new feature model in which the feature should be part of. If this parameter is null, the cloned feature's new feature model have to be the originals feature's feature model.
        newStructure - A new structure in which the feature should life. If this parameter is null, the cloned feature's new structure have to be the originals feature's structure.
        Returns:
        New instance f' of this feature f such that f != f' but f.equals(f') holds.
        Since:
        3.0, 3.0

      • getProperty

        IFeatureProperty getProperty()
        Returns the feature's properties. These properties depend on the IFeatureProperty implementation, but contain at least getters and setters for
        • a custom-defined description of the feature
        • a string-representation of the feature which is intended for display purposes
        • information about the feature status (dead, false-optional,...)
        • the state of the feature's selection in the GUI
        For user-defined properties, the IFeatureProperty implementation must be changed, or the method getCustomProperties() can be used.
        Returns:
        Implementation-specific feature properties.
        Since:
        3.0

      • getCustomProperties

        IPropertyContainer getCustomProperties()
        Returns the feature's custom-defined properties. These properties can be get and set without changes to the code base, or the need for a custom IFeatureProperty implementation (see getProperty()). Custom-Properties do map a Java primitive value to a string key and can stored to the file system.
        Returns:
        Implementation-independent custom feature properties.
        Since:
        3.0

      • getStructure

        @Nonnull
IFeatureStructure getStructure()
        Returns the feature structure, in which this feature lives in. The structure gives information about (and setter to) the children and the parent of this feature, and statement-related properties such as if this feature is part of an alternative group, or if it is abstract or hidden.

        Note: The returned object have to be non-null.
        Returns:
        The features structure properties.
        Since:
        3.0

      • createTooltip

        java.lang.String createTooltip(java.lang.Object... objects)
        Creates the tooltip for the feature. Used to have the same tooltip in the different views that are used within the project. The tooltip created for the feature depents on the parameter objects given to it.
        Parameters:
        objects - Objects to determine which content should be generated.
        Returns:
        Tooltip content as string
